abstract.value: The Eliot Katz Papers (1975-2017) includes essays, reports, newspaper clippings, photographs, personal writings, poetry and prose, and memorabilia related to Katz's activities as an activist and poet. The collection also contains correspondence between Katz and the poet Allen Ginsberg, which documents the influences in Katz's career as a poet and activist of human rights.  A significant portion of the collection consists of correspondence with other major activists and writers like Abbie Hoffman, Charles Bukowski, Adrienne Rich, Dave Dellinger, Tom Waits, and Amiri Baraka. As an advocate for homeless individuals and families of Central New Jersey, Katz dedicated himself to work with the Middlesex Interfaith Partners with the Homeless (MIPH) to institute housing and food programs. The collection also features newspaper clippings of poetry reviews and political events; photographs taken at literary events and political rallies; event posters to a variety of poetry readings; and memorabilia relating to his career as an activist and poet are also present in the collection. Of particular significance, the collection also features drafts and original manuscripts of Katz's poetry and other published works.

p.value: Identification of item, date; Eliot Katz Papers; TAM 722; box number; folder number; Tamiment Library/Robert F. Wagner Labor Archives, New York University.
Donated by Eliot Katz in 2017. The accession numbers associated with this gift are 2017.056 and 2017.079.

Eliot Katz (1957- ) is an American poet and activist. In the fall of 1976, as a student of Rutgers University, Katz met the prominent writer Allen Ginsberg. Over time, Katz developed a relationship with and became Ginsberg's apprentice. His interest in human rights causes and poetry was influenced greatly by Ginsberg. As a longtime resident of New Brunswick, New Jersey, Katz worked with Middlesex Interfaith Partners with the Homeless (MIPH) as an advocate for homeless families and individuals. He was a cofounder and former editor of <emph render="italic">Long Shot</emph> literary magazine, and his poems appear in numerous anthologies including,<emph render="italic">Blue Stones and Salt Hay: An Anthology of Contemporary New Jersey Poets</emph>, and<emph render="italic">Aloud: Voices from the Nuyorican Poets Cafe</emph>. He is the author of books of poetry, including:<emph render="italic">Space and Other Poems for Love, Laughs, and Social Transformation, Unlocking the Exits: Poems, Les voleurs au travail/Thieves at Work</emph>, and coeditor of<emph render="italic">Poems for the Nation: A Collection of Contemporary Political Poems</emph>. Katz currently resides in Hoboken, New Jersey.

The Eliot Katz Papers contains correspondence between Katz and Allen Ginsberg, as well as with major activists and writers like Abbie Hoffman, Charles Bukowski, Adrienne Rich, Dave Dellinger, Tom Waits, and Amiri Baraka. The collection also includes newspaper clippings of poetry reviews and political events; photographs taken at literary events and political rallies; event posters to a variety of poetry readings; and memorabilia relating to Katz's career as an activist and poet. Of particular significance, the collection also includes drafts and original manuscripts of Katz's poetry and other published works. The collection also contains video recordings of interviews with Katz in addition to electronic recordings of Katz's poetry activites.
